al links==\n* [http://www.britishpathe.com/search/query/mau+mau Archive newsreels] from [[Path\u00e9 News]]. Includes footage of: military operations against Mau Mau; the capture of Dedan Kimathi; capture of [[Waruhiu Itote|General China (Waruhiu Itote)]]; the survivors of the Lari massacre and the defendants' trial; Operation Anvil.\n* [http://www.colonialfilm.org.uk/search-content?keys=mau+mau&x=0&y=0 Colonial Film's archive footage of Mau Mau]\n* [https://www.scribd.com/dcasciani \"Lost\" Mau Mau-era government-documents posted by the BBC's Dominic Casciani]\n* [http://www.radiolab.org/story/mau-mau/ \"Mau-Mau\"] Podcast about the Mau Mau Uprising and British repression from Radiolab (WNYC \u2013 New York Public Radio)\n* [https://www.scribd.com/document/339189978/Mau-Mau-Emergency-Surrender-Pass-January-1955 Surrender Pass issued under Baring's 18 January 1955 Amnesty]\n\n{{Kenya topics}}\n{{British colonial campaigns}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:20th-century revolutions]]\n[[Category:Mau Mau Uprising| ]]\n[[Category:20th-century conflicts]]\n[[Category:African resistance to colonialism]]\n[[Category:Wars involving Kenya]]\n[[Category:Wars of independence]]\n[[Category:20th century in Kenya]]\n[[Category:Insurgencies in Africa]]\n[[Category:Resistance to the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Kikuyu]]\n[[Category:Proxy wars]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Kamba\u2192Kamba people", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mau_Mau_Uprising"}
{"title_page": "Mukesh Bhakar", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Mukesh Bhakar\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|6 May 1988|df=y}}\n| honorific-suffix = MLA Ladnun\n| image            = Mukesh Bhakar at Ladnun SDM Office for nomination.jpg\n| caption          = Bhakar at Ladnun SDM office\n| imagesize        = 250 px\n| birth_name       = Mukesh Bhakar\n| birth_place      = [[Ladnun, Rajasthan]], India\n| office1           = Member of Legislative Assembly (MLA) Ladnun\n| termstart1        = 17 December 2018\n| term_end1        = \n| assembly1        = [[Ladnun (Rajasthan Assembly constituency)|Ladnun]]\n| office2          = State President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]\n| term_start2      = 7 April 2020\n| office3          = State President, National Student\u2019s Union of India\n| term_start3      = January 2013\n| term_end3        = May 2015\n| office4          = [[National Students Union of India|National Secretary]]\n| term_start4      = 21 October 2015\n| term_end4        = 26 May 2018\n| office5          = Vice President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]\n| term_start5      = 22 November 2017\n| term_end5        = 6 April 2020\n| party            = [[Indian National Congress]]\n| parents          = Retd. Subedar Surjaram Bhakar (father)<br />Sohini Devi (mother)\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Rajasthan]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br /> [[University of Rajasthan|University of Rajasthan]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n}}\n\n'''Mukesh Bhakar''' (born 6 May 1988) is an Indian politician who is serving as the President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]], he represents also in [[Rajasthan Legislative Assembly]] from [[Ladnu|Ladnun]] of [[Nagaur district]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rajassembly.nic.in/MemberBioData.aspx|title=Rajasthan Legislative Assembly Member Information|website=rajassembly.nic.in}}</ref> As member of the [[Indian National Congress|Congress party]] <ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rajpcc.com/mukeshbhakar|title=Indian National Congress Party|website=www.rajpcc.com}}</ref>. Bhakar was previously State President of [[National Students' Union of India]] Rajasthan, the student wing of [[Indian National Congress]] from 2013 to 2015.\n\n== Political life ==\nHe elected State President of [[National Students' Union of India]] Rajasthan in 2013.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/news/RAJ-JAI-mukesh-bhakar-became-the-state-chief-of-nsui-4164425-NOR.html|title=NSUI \u0915\u0947 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0926\u0947\u0936\u093e\u0927\u094d\u092f\u0915\u094d\u0937 \u092c\u0928\u0947 \u092e\u0941\u0915\u0947\u0936 \u092d\u093e\u0915\u0930|date=31 January 2013|website=Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref>  During his tenure NSUI made come back in [[University of Rajasthan]] after 12 years in the Largest University of Rajasthan.<ref>https://www.bhaskar.com/rajasthan/jaipur/news/RAJ-JAI-10-candidates-for-presidents-post-rajasthan-4719233-NOR.html.</ref> After completion of his term National president nominated him National Secretary. Congress Party gave him an opportunity to contest Rajasthan State assembly elections 2018, where he successfully managed a win by margin of 12947 votes against 3 times MLA [[Thakur Manohar Singh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/election-result-2018/rajasthan-election-result-2018/nagaur/ladnun/mukesh-bhakar/|title=Ladnun Congress Candidate Mukesh Bhakar, Mukesh Bhakar vs Manohar Singh, \u0932\u093e\u0921\u0928\u0942\u0902 \u0938\u0940\u091f \u0938\u0947 \u0915\u093e\u0902\u0917\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0938 \u0909\u092e\u094d\u092e\u0940\u0926\u0935\u093e\u0930 \u092e\u0941\u0915\u0947\u0936 \u092d\u0915\u0930|website=Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/elections/rajasthan-election/article/ladnun-assembly-constituency-election-2018-rajasthan-assembly-polls-rajasthan-vasundhara-raje-bharatiya-janata-party-bjp-congress-sachin-pilot-manohar/320646|title=Ladnun Assembly Election Results 2018: Congress' Mukesh Bhakar won by 12,947 votes against BJP's sitting MLA|website=www.timesnownews.com}}</ref>. He won election for State President, [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]] over nearest candidate [[Amardin]] by 9872 votes.<ref>https://www.jagran.com/rajasthan/jaipur-congress-mla-mukesh-bhakar-appointed-as-rajasthan-pradesh-youth-congress-state-president-organization-elections-20172785.html</ref>\n\n== Positions held ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Position\n|-\n| 2009 - 10 || Unit President, National Students Union of India, University of Rajasthan\n|-\n| 2013 - 15 ||State President, National Students Union of India, NSUI Rajasthan\n|-\n| 2015 - 18 || National Secretary, National Students Union of India\n|-\n| 2018 \u2013 20  || State Vice President, Rajasthan Youth Congress\n|-\n| 2017 \u2013 cont. || PCC Member, Rajasthan Pradesh Congress Committee\n|-\n| 2017 \u2013 cont. || Member, All India Congress Committee\n|-\n| 2018 \u2013 cont. ||Member of Legislative Assembly (MLA) from Ladnun, Rajasthan State Assembly\n|-\n| 2019 \u2013 cont.  || Member of Committee on Petitions, Rajasthan State Assembly\n|-\n| 2020 \u2013 cont.  || State President, Rajasthan Youth Congress\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{twitter.com|mukeshbhakar_}}\n\n{{Indian National Congress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhakar, Mukesh}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani people]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani politicians]]\n[[Category:Rajasthan MLAs 2018\u2013]]\n[[Category:People from Nagaur district]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indian politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name             = Mukesh Bhakar\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|6 May 1988|df=y}}\n| honorific-suffix = MLA Ladnun\n| image            = Mukesh Bhakar at Ladnun SDM Office for nomination.jpg\n| caption          = Bhakar at Ladnun SDM office\n| imagesize        = 250 px\n| birth_name       = Mukesh Bhakar\n| birth_place      = [[Ladnun, Rajasthan]], India\n| office1           = Member of Legislative Assembly (MLA) Ladnun\n| termstart1        = 17 December 2018\n| governor         = [[Kalraj Mishra]]\n| term_end1        = \n| assembly1        = [[Ladnun (Rajasthan Assembly constituency)|Ladnun]]\n| office2          = State President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]\n| term_start2      = 7 April 2020\n| office3          = State President, National Student\u2019s Union of India\n| term_start3      = January 2013\n| term_end3        = May 2015\n| office4          = [[National Students Union of India|National Secretary]]\n| term_start4      = 21 October 2015\n| term_end4        = 26 May 2018\n| office5          = Vice President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]]\n| term_start5      = 22 November 2017\n| term_end5        = 6 April 2020\n| party            = [[Indian National Congress]]\n| parents          = Retd. Subedar Surjaram Bhakar (father)<br />Sohini Devi (mother)\n| alma_mater       = [[University of Rajasthan]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br /> [[University of Rajasthan|University of Rajasthan]] ([[Master of Arts|MA]])\n}}\n\n'''Mukesh Bhakar''' (born 6 May 1988) is an Indian politician who is serving as the President of the [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]], he represents also in [[Rajasthan Legislative Assembly]] from [[Ladnu|Ladnun]] of [[Nagaur district]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://rajassembly.nic.in/MemberBioData.aspx|title=Rajasthan Legislative Assembly Member Information|website=rajassembly.nic.in}}</ref> As member of the [[Indian National Congress|Congress party]] <ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.rajpcc.com/mukeshbhakar|title=Indian National Congress Party|website=www.rajpcc.com}}</ref>. Bhakar was previously State President of [[National Students' Union of India]] Rajasthan, the student wing of [[Indian National Congress]] from 2013 to 2015.\n\n== Political life ==\nHe elected State President of [[National Students' Union of India]] Rajasthan in 2013.<ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/news/RAJ-JAI-mukesh-bhakar-became-the-state-chief-of-nsui-4164425-NOR.html|title=NSUI \u0915\u0947 \u092a\u094d\u0930\u0926\u0947\u0936\u093e\u0927\u094d\u092f\u0915\u094d\u0937 \u092c\u0928\u0947 \u092e\u0941\u0915\u0947\u0936 \u092d\u093e\u0915\u0930|date=31 January 2013|website=Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref>  During his tenure NSUI made come back in [[University of Rajasthan]] after 12 years in the Largest University of Rajasthan.<ref>https://www.bhaskar.com/rajasthan/jaipur/news/RAJ-JAI-10-candidates-for-presidents-post-rajasthan-4719233-NOR.html.</ref> After completion of his term National president nominated him National Secretary. Congress Party gave him an opportunity to contest Rajasthan State assembly elections 2018, where he successfully managed a win by margin of 12947 votes against 3 times MLA [[Thakur Manohar Singh]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bhaskar.com/election-result-2018/rajasthan-election-result-2018/nagaur/ladnun/mukesh-bhakar/|title=Ladnun Congress Candidate Mukesh Bhakar, Mukesh Bhakar vs Manohar Singh, \u0932\u093e\u0921\u0928\u0942\u0902 \u0938\u0940\u091f \u0938\u0947 \u0915\u093e\u0902\u0917\u094d\u0930\u0947\u0938 \u0909\u092e\u094d\u092e\u0940\u0926\u0935\u093e\u0930 \u092e\u0941\u0915\u0947\u0936 \u092d\u0915\u0930|website=Dainik Bhaskar}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timesnownews.com/elections/rajasthan-election/article/ladnun-assembly-constituency-election-2018-rajasthan-assembly-polls-rajasthan-vasundhara-raje-bharatiya-janata-party-bjp-congress-sachin-pilot-manohar/320646|title=Ladnun Assembly Election Results 2018: Congress' Mukesh Bhakar won by 12,947 votes against BJP's sitting MLA|website=www.timesnownews.com}}</ref>. He won election for State President, [[Rajasthan Youth Congress]] over nearest candidate [[Amardin]] by 9872 votes.<ref>https://www.jagran.com/rajasthan/jaipur-congress-mla-mukesh-bhakar-appointed-as-rajasthan-pradesh-youth-congress-state-president-organization-elections-20172785.html</ref>\n\n== Positions held ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Position\n|-\n| 2009 - 10 || Unit President, National Students Union of India, University of Rajasthan\n|-\n| 2013 - 15 ||State President, National Students Union of India, NSUI Rajasthan\n|-\n| 2015 - 18 || National Secretary, National Students Union of India\n|-\n| 2018 \u2013 20  || State Vice President, Rajasthan Youth Congress\n|-\n| 2017 \u2013 cont. || PCC Member, Rajasthan Pradesh Congress Committee\n|-\n| 2017 \u2013 cont. || Member, All India Congress Committee\n|-\n| 2018 \u2013 cont. ||Member of Legislative Assembly (MLA) from Ladnun, Rajasthan State Assembly\n|-\n| 2019 \u2013 cont.  || Member of Committee on Petitions, Rajasthan State Assembly\n|-\n| 2020 \u2013 cont.  || State President, Rajasthan Youth Congress\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{twitter.com|mukeshbhakar_}}\n\n{{Indian National Congress}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bhakar, Mukesh}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani people]]\n[[Category:Indian National Congress politicians]]\n[[Category:Rajasthani politicians]]\n[[Category:Rajasthan MLAs 2018\u2013]]\n[[Category:People from Nagaur district]]\n", "name_user": "Mukesh Bhakar 0013", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mukesh_Bhakar"}
{"title_page": "Got to Be Real", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Got to Be Real\n| cover      = Got_to_Be_Real_NZ.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Cheryl Lynn]]\n| album      = [[Cheryl Lynn (album)|Cheryl Lynn]]\n| B-side     = Come in from the Rain\n| released   = August 14, 1978<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=Cheryl+Lynn#search_section |title=Gold & Platinum |publisher=RIAA |date= |accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n| format     = {{flat list|\n*[[Gramophone record|7-inch]]\n*[[Twelve-inch single|12-inch]]}}\n| recorded   = April 1978\n| studio     = Sunset Sound Studios<br/><small>([[Hollywood]], [[California]])</small>\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Disco]]<ref>{{cite web|author=AllMusic Review by Andy Kellman |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/cheryl-lynn-mw0000651384 |title=Cheryl Lynn - Cheryl Lynn &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2017-02-01}}</ref>\n| length     = 5:07\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer     = {{flatlist|\n*Cheryl Lynn\n*[[David Paich]]\n*[[David Foster]]}}\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*David Paich\n*[[Marty Paich]]}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = Star Love\n| next_year  = 1979\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = single\n | cover   =\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption =\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Got to Be Real'''\" is a song by American singer [[Cheryl Lynn]] from her 1978 [[Cheryl Lynn (album)|self-titled]] debut studio [[album]]. The song, which was Lynn's debut [[Single (music)|single]], was written by Lynn, [[David Paich]] and [[David Foster]], and is one of the most popular and well-known in [[disco]] music.\n\n==Recording==\nFor the recording, David Shields played bass, [[David Paich]] played keyboards, [[James Gadson]] played drums and [[Ray Parker, Jr.]] was the session guitarist.\n\n==Chart performance==\nIn the United States, \"Got to Be Real\" spent three weeks at number twelve on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and hit number one on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Hot Soul Singles]] chart in early 1979.<ref>{{cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-2004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=368}}</ref> Along with the album tracks \"Star Love\" and \"You Saved My Day\", \"Got to Be Real\" peaked at number eleven on the [[Dance Club Songs|National Disco Action Top 40]] chart.<ref>{{cite book |title= Hot Dance/Disco: 1974-2003|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=162}}</ref> The song was used for a 2010 UK TV advertising campaign for [[Marks & Spencer]], a [[department store]], and it re-entered the main charts at number 78 for the week ending April 4, the next week peaking at number 70.<ref name=\"chartstats1\">[https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/Got%20To%20Be%20Real \"Got to Be Real Official Charts Company history\"]. OfficialCharts.com. Retrieved 2011-29-5.</ref><ref name=\"chartstats2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artists/|title=Cheryl Lynn Official Charts Companyhistory|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=2009-12-12}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\"Got to Be Real\" was inducted into the [[Dance Music Hall of Fame]] on September 19, 2005. RIAA Platinum Certification. In 2017, [[ShortList|ShortList's]] Dave Fawbert listed the song as containing \"one of the greatest [[Modulation (music)|key changes]] in music history\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shortlist.com/entertainment/music/the-best-key-changes-music/329120|title=The 19 greatest key changes in music history|publisher=[[ShortList]]|date=October 1, 2017|accessdate=January 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing and formats==\n'''US 7-inch vinyl single'''\n\n# \"Got to Be Real\" \u2013 3:42\n# \"Come in from the Rain\" \u2013 3:35\n\n'''US 12-inch vinyl single'''\n\n# \"Got to Be Real\" \u2013 5:10\n# \"Come in from the Rain\" \u2013 3:35\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1978\u201379)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canada Top Singles (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|16\n|-\n|New Zealand ([[RIANZ]])<ref>[http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20rianz&qsongid=3383#n_view_location Flavour of New Zealand, 15 April 1979]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|23\n|-\n|UK Singles ([[Official Charts Company]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|70\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Hot Soul Singles]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''Billboard'' [[Dance Club Songs|National Disco Action Top 40]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19790210.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-11-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113065538/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19790210.html |archivedate=2014-11-13 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|}\n\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1979)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Canada Top Singles (''RPM'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6855b&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=d82phtgpm63ilptc88am0pdri7 |title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|124\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1979.htm |title=Top 100 Hits of 1979/Top 100 Songs of 1979 |website=Musicoutfitters.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|69\n|-\n|US ''Cash Box''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/1979YESP.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-04-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304060014/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/1979YESP.html |archivedate=2016-03-04 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|89\n|}\n\n===Certifications and sales===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|type=single|artist=Cheryl Lynn|title=Got_ to_Be_ Real|award=Platinum|relyear=1979|certyear=2001|certmonth=September|certref=<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>|salesamount=1,000,000|accessdate=2016-06-08}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom}}\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Cover versions==\n* In 2004, [[Mary J. Blige]] and [[Will Smith]] covered the song for the soundtrack to the animated film ''[[Shark Tale]]''.\n* In 1998, [[Patti LaBelle]] and [[Mariah Carey]] covered the song on LaBelle's Grammy-winning live album ''[[Live! One Night Only]]'', the same version used as the title and theme song of the [[parody]] [[web series|digital series]] ''[[Got 2B Real: The Diva Variety Show|Got 2B Real]]'', which featured both Labelle and Carey as lead characters.\n*In 1994, [[Erik (singer)|Erik]] covered the single, resulting in a UK club smash hit,<ref name=\"Davies1998\">{{cite book|last=Davies|first=Chris|title=British and American hit singles: 51 years of transatlantic hits, 1946-1997|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=bp8JAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=8 August 2011|date=September 1998|publisher=BT Batsford|page=1374}}</ref> rising to number 42 in the UK singles chart.<ref>https://www.officialcharts.com/artist/29514/erik/</ref>\n\n==Appearances in other media==\n* The song was prominently featured in the 1990 documentary ''[[Paris Is Burning (film)|Paris Is Burning]]'', which chronicles the [[ball culture]] of [[New York City]] and the poor, [[African American]] and [[Hispanic and Latino Americans|Latino]] [[gay]] and [[transgender]] community involved in it.\n* Whit Stillman's film ''[[The Last Days of Disco]]'' includes the song on its soundtrack.\n* In 1998, in the first-season episode \"Head Case\" of the [[sitcom]] ''[[Will and Grace]]'', [[Will Truman|Will]] sings this song in the bathroom while he shaves, to which [[Grace Adler|Grace]] responds \"We're just like fifty men and a mirrored ball away from being a gay disco\".\n* The song was also included as a playable song in the North American version of [[Dance Dance Revolution SuperNOVA 2]].\n* In 2001, the song appeared in the fourth season ''[[Sex and the City]]'' episode, \"The Real Me\", where [[Carrie Bradshaw]] becomes a model for a day.\n* In 2006, the song featured in ''[[The Pink Panther (2006 film)|The Pink Panther]]'', during some of the New York scenes.\n* In March 2010, UK department store [[Marks and Spencer]] used \"Got To Be Real\" in adverts for their new Spring Collection.\n* The song also is used as the theme song for italian cinema show ''Supercinema''.\n\n==See also==\n* [[R&B number-one hits of 1979 (USA)|Soul number-one singles of 1979 (US)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|cheryl-lynn|got-to-be-real}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* [{{Allmusic|class=song|id=t2672612|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic Entry]\n\n{{Cheryl Lynn}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Got To Be Real}}\n[[Category:1978 singles]]\n[[Category:Cheryl Lynn songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Debut singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by David Foster]]\n[[Category:Songs written by David Paich]]\n[[Category:1978 songs]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records singles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Got to Be Real\n| cover      = Got_to_Be_Real_NZ.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Cheryl Lynn]]\n| album      = [[Cheryl Lynn (album)|Cheryl Lynn]]\n| B-side     = Come in from the Rain\n| released   = August 14, 1978<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.riaa.com/gold-platinum/?tab_active=default-award&se=Cheryl+Lynn#search_section |title=Gold & Platinum |publisher=RIAA |date= |accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n| format     = {{flat list|\n*[[Gramophone record|7-inch]]\n*[[Twelve-inch single|12-inch]]}}\n| recorded   = April 1978\n| studio     = Sunset Sound Studios<br/><small>([[Hollywood]], [[California]])</small>\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Disco]]<ref>{{cite web|author=AllMusic Review by Andy Kellman |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/cheryl-lynn-mw0000651384 |title=Cheryl Lynn - Cheryl Lynn &#124; Songs, Reviews, Credits |publisher=AllMusic |date= |accessdate=2017-02-01}}</ref>\n| length     = 5:07\n| label      = [[Columbia Records|Columbia]]\n| writer     = {{flatlist|\n*Cheryl Lynn\n*[[David Paich]]\n*[[David Foster]]}}\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*David Paich\n*[[Marty Paich]]}}\n| prev_title =\n| prev_year  =\n| next_title = [[Cheryl Lynn (album)#Track listing|Star Love]]\n| next_year  = 1979\n| misc       = {{Extra album cover\n | header  = Alternative cover\n | type    = single\n | cover   =\n | border  =\n | alt     =\n | caption =\n}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Got to Be Real'''\" is a song by American singer [[Cheryl Lynn]] from her 1978 [[Cheryl Lynn (album)|self-titled]] debut studio [[album]]. The song, which was Lynn's debut [[Single (music)|single]], was written by Lynn, [[David Paich]] and [[David Foster]], and is one of the most popular and well-known in [[disco]] music.\n\n==Recording==\nFor the recording, David Shields played bass, [[David Paich]] played keyboards, [[James Gadson]] played drums and [[Ray Parker, Jr.]] was the session guitarist.\n\n==Chart performance==\nIn the United States, \"Got to Be Real\" spent three weeks at number twelve on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]] and hit number one on the [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Hot Soul Singles]] chart in early 1979.<ref>{{cite book |title= Top R&B/Hip-Hop Singles: 1942-2004|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=368}}</ref> Along with the album tracks \"Star Love\" and \"You Saved My Day\", \"Got to Be Real\" peaked at number eleven on the [[Dance Club Songs|National Disco Action Top 40]] chart.<ref>{{cite book |title= Hot Dance/Disco: 1974-2003|last=Whitburn |first=Joel |authorlink=Joel Whitburn |year=2004 |publisher=Record Research |page=162}}</ref> The song was used for a 2010 UK TV advertising campaign for [[Marks & Spencer]], a [[department store]], and it re-entered the main charts at number 78 for the week ending April 4, the next week peaking at number 70.<ref name=\"chartstats1\">[https://www.officialcharts.com/search/singles/Got%20To%20Be%20Real \"Got to Be Real Official Charts Company history\"]. OfficialCharts.com. Retrieved 2011-29-5.</ref><ref name=\"chartstats2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.officialcharts.com/artists/|title=Cheryl Lynn Official Charts Companyhistory|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=2009-12-12}}</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\n\"Got to Be Real\" was inducted into the [[Dance Music Hall of Fame]] on September 19, 2005. RIAA Platinum Certification. In 2017, [[ShortList|ShortList's]] Dave Fawbert listed the song as containing \"one of the greatest [[Modulation (music)|key changes]] in music history\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.shortlist.com/entertainment/music/the-best-key-changes-music/329120|title=The 19 greatest key changes in music history|publisher=[[ShortList]]|date=October 1, 2017|accessdate=January 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing and formats==\n'''US 7-inch vinyl single'''\n\n# \"Got to Be Real\" \u2013 3:42\n# \"Come in from the Rain\" \u2013 3:35\n\n'''US 12-inch vinyl single'''\n\n# \"Got to Be Real\" \u2013 5:10\n# \"Come in from the Rain\" \u2013 3:35\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n{{col-begin}}\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1978\u201379)\n!align=\"left\"|Peak<br />position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|Canada Top Singles (''[[RPM (magazine)|RPM]]'')\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|16\n|-\n|New Zealand ([[RIANZ]])<ref>[http://www.flavourofnz.co.nz/index.php?qpageID=search%20rianz&qsongid=3383#n_view_location Flavour of New Zealand, 15 April 1979]</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|23\n|-\n|UK Singles ([[Official Charts Company]])\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|70\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|12\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''Billboard'' [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs|Hot Soul Singles]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|1\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''Billboard'' [[Dance Club Songs|National Disco Action Top 40]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|11\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US ''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cash Box]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19790210.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-11-13 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141113065538/http://50.6.195.142/archives/70s_files/19790210.html |archivedate=2014-11-13 }}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|10\n|}\n\n{{col-2}}\n\n===Year-end charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!align=\"left\"|Chart (1979)\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n|Canada Top Singles (''RPM'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.collectionscanada.gc.ca/rpm/028020-119.01-e.php?&file_num=nlc008388.6855b&type=1&interval=50&PHPSESSID=d82phtgpm63ilptc88am0pdri7 |title=Item Display - RPM - Library and Archives Canada |website=Collectionscanada.gc.ca |date= |accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|124\n|-\n|US ''Billboard'' Hot 100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.musicoutfitters.com/topsongs/1979.htm |title=Top 100 Hits of 1979/Top 100 Songs of 1979 |website=Musicoutfitters.com |date= |accessdate=2016-10-13}}</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|69\n|-\n|US ''Cash Box''<ref>{{cite web|url=http:/