sco]]'' includes the song on its soundtrack.\n* In 1998, in the first-season episode \"Head Case\" of the [[sitcom]] ''[[Will and Grace]]'', [[Will Truman|Will]] sings this song in the bathroom while he shaves, to which [[Grace Adler|Grace]] responds \"We're just like fifty men and a mirrored ball away from being a gay disco\".\n* The song was also included as a playable song in the North American version of [[Dance Dance Revolution SuperNOVA 2]].\n* In 2001, the song appeared in the fourth season ''[[Sex and the City]]'' episode, \"The Real Me\", where [[Carrie Bradshaw]] becomes a model for a day.\n* In 2006, the song featured in ''[[The Pink Panther (2006 film)|The Pink Panther]]'', during some of the New York scenes.\n* In March 2010, UK department store [[Marks and Spencer]] used \"Got To Be Real\" in adverts for their new Spring Collection.\n* The song also is used as the theme song for italian cinema show ''Supercinema''.\n\n==See also==\n* [[R&B number-one hits of 1979 (USA)|Soul number-one singles of 1979 (US)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|cheryl-lynn|got-to-be-real}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n* [{{Allmusic|class=song|id=t2672612|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic Entry]\n\n{{Cheryl Lynn}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Got To Be Real}}\n[[Category:1978 singles]]\n[[Category:Cheryl Lynn songs]]\n[[Category:Billboard Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Debut singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by David Foster]]\n[[Category:Songs written by David Paich]]\n[[Category:1978 songs]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records singles]]\n", "name_user": "189.172.64.135", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Got_to_Be_Real"}
{"title_page": "Roswell, New Mexico", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2018}}\n{{For|the TV series|Roswell, New Mexico (TV series)}}\n \n{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name            = Roswell, New Mexico\n|settlement_type          = [[List of cities in New Mexico|City]]\n|nickname                 = \n|image_skyline            = Roswell NM Main Street.jpg\n|imagesize                = 270px\n|image_caption            = Main Street in downtown Roswell\n|image_flag               = Flag of Roswell, New Mexico.svg\n|image_seal               = Roswell NM logo.png\n|image_map                = Chaves_County_New_Mexico_Incorporated_and_Unincorporated_areas_Roswell_Highlighted.svg\n|map_caption              = Location within Chaves County\n|image_map1               = \n|mapsize1                 = \n|map_caption1             = \n| pushpin_map = New Mexico#USA\n| pushpin_map_caption = Location within New Mexico##Location within the United States\n| pushpin_label = Roswell\n| pushpin_relief = 1\n|subdivision_type         = Country\n|subdivision_type1        = [[U.S. state|State]]\n|subdivision_type2        = [[List of counties in New Mexico|County]]\n|subdivision_name         = United States\n|subdivision_name1        = [[New Mexico]]\n|subdivision_name2        = [[Chaves County, New Mexico|Chaves]]\n|government_type          = \n|leader_title             = Mayor\n|leader_name              = [[Dennis Kintigh]]\n|established_date         = \n|area_magnitude           = 1 E9\n|area_total_km2           = 77.5\n|area_total_sq_mi         = \n|area_land_km2            = 77.3\n|area_land_sq_mi          = \n|area_water_km2           = 0.1\n|area_water_sq_mi         = \n|elevation_m              = 1089\n|elevation_ft             = 3573\n|coordinates              = {{coord|33|23|14|N|104|31|41|W|region:US-NM|display=inline,title}}\n|population_as_of         = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n|population_note          = \n|population_footnotes     = \n|population_total         = 48411\n|timezone                 = [[Mountain Standard Time|Mountain]]\n|utc_offset               = \u221207:00\n|timezone_DST             = [[Daylight saving time|DST]]\n|utc_offset_DST           = \u221206:00\n|website                  = {{URL|www.roswell-nm.gov}}\n|postal_code_type         = [[ZIP Code]]s\n|postal_code              = 88201-88203\n|area_code                = [[Area code 575|575]]\n|blank_name               = [[Federal Information Processing Standard|FIPS code]]\n|blank_info               = 35-64930\n|blank1_name              = [[Geographic Names Information System|GNIS]] feature ID\n|blank1_info              = 0894171\n|footnotes                = \n|pop_est_as_of = 2018\n|pop_est_footnotes = <ref name=\"USCensusEst2018\"/>\n|population_est = 47635\n|population_density_sq_mi = auto\n|population_density_km2 = auto\n|unit_pref = Imperial\n}}\n\n'''Roswell''' is a city in, and the [[County seat|seat]] of, [[Chaves County, New Mexico|Chaves County]] in the U.S. state of [[New Mexico]], the county forms the entirety of the [[List of micropolitan areas in New Mexico|Roswell micropolitan area]].<ref name=\"GR6\">{{cite web| url=http://www.naco.org/Counties/Pages/FindACounty.aspx|accessdate=June 7, 2011|title=Find a County|publisher=National Association of Counties}}</ref> As of the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]] it had a population of 48,411,<ref name=\"Census 2010\">{{cite web| url=http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US3564930| archive-url=https://archive.today/20200212192452/http://factfinder.census.gov/bkmk/table/1.0/en/DEC/10_DP/G001/1600000US3564930| url-status=dead| archive-date=February 12, 2020| title=Geographic Identifiers: 2010 Demographic Profile Data (G001): Roswell city, New Mexico (revision of 01-02-2013)| publisher=U.S. Census Bureau, American Factfinder| accessdate=October 16, 2014}}</ref> making it the fifth-largest city in New Mexico. It is home of [[New Mexico Military Institute]] (NMMI), founded in 1891. The city is also the location of an [[Eastern New Mexico University]] campus. [[Bitter Lake National Wildlife Refuge]] is located a few miles northeast of the city on the [[Pecos River]]. [[Bottomless Lakes State Park]] is located {{convert|12|mi}} east of Roswell on [[U.S. Route 380|US 380]].\n\nThe [[Roswell UFO incident]] was named after the town, though the crash site of the alleged [[UFO]] was some {{convert|75|mi}} from Roswell and closer to [[Corona, New Mexico|Corona]]. The investigation and debris recovery was handled by the local [[Roswell Army Air Field]]. In the 1930s, Roswell was a site for much of [[Robert H. Goddard]]'s early [[rocket]]ry work. The Roswell Museum and Art Center maintains an exhibit which includes a recreation of Goddard's [[rocket engine]] development workshop.\n\nRoswell's tourism industry is based on [[aerospace engineering]] and [[ufology]] museums and businesses, as well as [[extraterrestrial intelligence|alien]]-themed and [[spacecraft]]-themed iconography. The city also relies on New Mexico and Americana related tourism. Local [[American folk music|American folk]] and [[New Mexico music]] performances occur near Pioneer Plaza and in parks around the city. It is a center for [[acequia]]-similar irrigated farming, dairying, and ranching, it also the location of several manufacturing, distribution, and petroleum related facilities.  This regional pride has resulted in Roswell receiving the [[All-America City Award]] multiple times, in 1978\u201379 and 2002.\n\n==History==\n[[image:Historical-museum.jpg|thumb|left|The White family home, built in 1912, is now a museum.]]\n[[image:Chaves County Courthouse.jpg|thumb|left|The Chaves County courthouse]]\n[[File:Roswell New Mexico Flood.jpg|thumb|left|Roswell flood]]\nThe first non-indigenous settlers of the area around Roswell were a group of pioneers from [[Missouri]], who attempted to start a settlement {{convert|15|mi}} southwest of what is now Roswell in 1865, but were forced to abandon the site because of a lack of water. It was called Missouri Plaza. It also had many Hispanic people from [[Lincoln, New Mexico]]. [[John Chisum]] had his famous Jingle Bob Ranch about {{convert|5|mi|0}} from the center of Roswell, at South Spring Acres. At the time, it was the largest ranch in the United States.\n\nVan C. Smith, a businessman from [[Omaha, Nebraska]], and his partner, Aaron Wilburn, constructed two [[adobe]] buildings in 1869 that began what is now Roswell. The two buildings became the settlement's general store, post office, and sleeping quarters for paying guests. In 1871, Smith filed a claim with the federal government for the land around the buildings, and on August 20, 1873, he became the town's first [[postmaster]]. Smith was the son of Roswell Smith, a prominent lawyer in [[Lafayette, Indiana]], and Annie Ellsworth, daughter of U.S. Patent Commissioner [[Henry Leavitt Ellsworth]]. He called the town Roswell, after his father's first name.\n\nIn 1877, Captain Joseph Calloway Lea and his family bought out Smith and Wilburn's claim and became the owners of most of the land of Roswell and the area surrounding it. The town was relatively quiet during the [[Lincoln County War]] (1877\u20131879). A major [[aquifer]] was discovered when merchant Nathan Jaffa had a well drilled in his back yard on Richardson Avenue in 1890, resulting in the area's first major growth and development spurt. The growth continued when a railroad was built through town in 1893.\n\nDuring World War II, a [[prisoner-of-war camp]] was located in nearby [[Orchard Park, New Mexico|Orchard Park]]. The German prisoners of war were used to do major infrastructure work in Roswell, such as paving the banks of the [[North Spring River]]. Some POWs used rocks of different sizes to create the outline of an [[iron cross]] among the stones covering the north bank. Later, the iron cross was covered with a thin layer of concrete. In the 1980s, a crew cleaning the river bed cleared off the concrete and revealed the outline once more. The small park just south of the cross was then known as Iron Cross Park. On November 11, 1996, the park was renamed POW/MIA Park. The park displays a piece of the [[Berlin Wall]], presented to the city of Roswell by the [[German Air Force]].\n\nRoswell was a location of military importance from 1941 to 1967. In 1967, the [[Walker Air Force Base]] was decommissioned. After the closure of the base, Roswell capitalized on its pleasant climate and reinvented itself as a [[retirement community]].\n\n[[Image:RoswellDailyRecordJuly8,1947.jpg|thumb|right|200px|''[[Roswell Daily Record]]'', July 8, 1947, announcing the \"capture\" of a \"flying saucer\"]]\n[[Image:International UFO Museum and Research Center Roswell New Mexico.jpg|right|thumb|200px|[[International UFO Museum]]]]\n\nRoswell has benefited from interest in the alleged [[Roswell UFO incident|UFO incident of 1947]]. It was the report of an object that crashed in the general vicinity in June or July 1947, allegedly an [[extraterrestrial spacecraft]] and its [[Extraterrestrial life|alien]] occupants. Since the late 1970s, the incident has been the subject of intense controversy and of a [[conspiracy theory]] regarding a classified program named \"[[Project Mogul|Mogul]]\". Many [[Unidentified flying object|UFO]] proponents maintain that an alien craft was found and its occupants were captured, and that the military then engaged in a cover-up. In recent times, the business community has deliberately sought out tourists interested in UFOs, science fiction, and aliens.\n\nRoswell hosted the [[Red Bull Stratos|record-breaking skydive]] by [[Felix Baumgartner]] on October 14, 2012.<ref>{{cite news| last=Llorca| first=Juan| title=Felix Baumgartner Completes Record-Setting Jump| url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/10/14/felix-baumgartner-jump-redbull-skydive_n_1965299.html| work=Huffington Post| accessdate=October 17, 2012| date=October 14, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nRoswell is located in southeastern [[New Mexico]], approximately {{convert|7|mi|0|abbr=on}} west of the [[Pecos River]] and some {{convert|40|mi|abbr=on}} east of highlands that rise to the [[Sierra Blanca (New Mexico)|Sierra Blanca]] range. U.S. Routes [[U.S. Route 70 in New Mexico|70]], [[U.S. Route 285 (New Mexico)|285]] and [[U.S. Route 380 (New Mexico)|380]] intersect in the city. US 70 leads northeast {{convert|111|mi|abbr=on}} to [[Clovis, New Mexico|Clovis]] and {{convert|117|mi|abbr=on}} west to [[Alamogordo, New Mexico|Alamogordo]]; US 285 leads north {{convert|192|mi|abbr=on}} to [[Santa Fe, New Mexico|Santa Fe]] and south {{convert|76|mi|abbr=on}} to [[Carlsbad, New Mexico|Carlsbad]]; and US 380 leads east {{convert|134|mi|abbr=on}} to [[Brownfield, Texas]], and west {{convert|164|mi|abbr=on}} to [[Socorro, New Mexico|Socorro]].\n\nAccording to the [[United States Census Bureau]], Roswell has a total area of {{convert|77.5|km2|order=flip}}, of which {{convert|77.3|km2|order=flip}} is land and {{convert|0.1|km2|order=flip|2}}, or 0.19%, is covered by water.<ref name=\"Census 2010\"/>\n[[File:Main Street Roswell.jpg|left|thumb|250px|Main Street]]\n\n===Climate===\nRoswell is located in the [[High Plains (United States)|High Plains]] and has four very distinct seasons, giving it a ''BSk'' or ''BSh'' [[semiarid climate]] according to the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]]. Winters are cold, but usually sunny, and [[snowfall]] is a common occurrence. Spring is mild and usually warm, but can still be cold on occasion. Summers are hot (as is common with the High Plains of New Mexico and [[Colorado]]) and, quite frequently, the temperature rises above 100&nbsp;\u00b0F, which can be unpleasant. The North American [[monsoon]] occurs during the summer, and can bring torrential downpours, severe [[thunderstorms]] (with high winds and [[hail]]) and sometimes even [[tornadoes]]. The rain can provide a cooling relief from the scorching great plains heat. Fall is mild and pleasant, but can be cold. Snow is possible in October and November.\n\nThe record low in Roswell is {{convert|-24|F|0}} on January 11, 1962 and February 8, 1933.<ref name = NOAA/> The record high is {{convert|114|F|0}} on June 27, 1994.<ref>[http://www.weather.com/weather/wxclimatology/daily/USNM0267?climoMonth=6 June Daily Averages for Roswell, NM ''Weather.com'' Retrieved June 12, 2012]</ref>\n\n{{Weather box\n|location = Roswell, New Mexico (Roswell Air Park), 1981\u20132010 normals, extremes 1893\u2013present\n|single line = Y\n|Jan record high F =  88\n|Feb record high F =  88\n|Mar record high F =  95\n|Apr record high F = 102\n|May record high F = 107\n|Jun record high F = 114\n|Jul record high F = 111\n|Aug record high F = 111\n|Sep record high F = 104\n|Oct record high F =  99\n|Nov record high F =  94\n|Dec record high F =  84\n|year record high F = 114\n|Jan high F = 55.1\n|Feb high F = 60.7\n|Mar high F = 68.3\n|Apr high F = 76.8\n|May high F = 85.4\n|Jun high F = 93.2\n|Jul high F = 93.7\n|Aug high F = 91.7\n|Sep high F = 85.6\n|Oct high F = 75.7\n|Nov high F = 64.3\n|Dec high F = 54.6\n|year high F = 75.4\n|Jan low F = 26.1\n|Feb low F = 30.7\n|Mar low F = 36.9\n|Apr low F = 44.7\n|May low F = 54.7\n|Jun low F = 63.2\n|Jul low F = 67.0\n|Aug low F = 65.8\n|Sep low F = 58.5\n|Oct low F = 46.5\n|Nov low F = 34.3\n|Dec low F = 26.1\n|year low F = 46.2\n|Jan record low F = \u221224\n|Feb record low F = \u221224\n|Mar record low F =  \u22125\n|Apr record low F =  17\n|May record low F =  27\n|Jun record low F =  40\n|Jul record low F =  52\n|Aug record low F =  48\n|Sep record low F =  30\n|Oct record low F =  14\n|Nov record low F =  \u22126\n|Dec record low F = \u221210\n|year record low F= \u221224\n|precipitation colour = green\n|Jan precipitation inch = 0.38\n|Feb precipitation inch = 0.42\n|Mar precipitation inch = 0.51\n|Apr precipitation inch = 0.61\n|May precipitation inch = 1.25\n|Jun precipitation inch = 1.73\n|Jul pre